                <div class="content-item"><div class="item">
        <article>
            <div class="author"><a href="/authors/donaldson.simon-k" title="Author Profile">Donaldson, S. K.</a></div>
    
    
    
            <h2 class="title">
                <strong>Gluing techniques in the cohomology of moduli spaces.</strong>
                <i>(English)</i>
                <a class="label nowrap" href="/0870.57039">Zbl 0870.57039</a>
            </h2>
            <div class="source">
                
    
        Goldberg, Lisa R. (ed.) et al., Topological methods in modern mathematics. Proceedings of a symposium in honor of John Milnor&rsquo;s sixtieth birthday, held at the State University of New York at Stony Brook, USA, June 14-June 21, 1991. Houston, TX: Publish or Perish, Inc. 137-170 (1993).
            </div>
            <div class="abstract">We discuss certain homological properties of moduli spaces of flat connections over Riemann surfaces. These moduli spaces have been studied from many points of view, ranging from algebraic geometry to quantum physics, and the problem that we consider falls into a rather general pattern in moduli theory. If \(M\) is a moduli space of connections or holomorphic structures on a bundle over a manifold \(Z\) then, under some technical conditions, there is a universal bundle \({\mathbf E}\) over the product \(M\times Z\). Any characteristic class \(c({\mathbf E})\) in \(H^d (M\times Z)\) yields, by the &ldquo;slant product&rdquo; in homology, a map \(\mu_c: H_i(Z) \to H^{d-i} (M)\), so we obtain a collection of &ldquo;universal&rdquo; cohomology classes over the moduli space. Suppose \(M\) is a compact oriented \(n\)-manifold and that \(\Omega\) is a product of these cohomology classes of total degree \(n\). Then we obtain a numerical invariant \(\langle\Omega, [M]\rangle\) of the moduli space by evaluating on the fundamental class &ndash; or, in terms of de Rham cohomology, by integration over moduli space. The general problem we have in mind is the calculation of these numbers.<br class="zbmathjax-paragraph">We focus on the case when the base space \(Z\) is a surface, but the motivation for the work came largely from 4-manifold theory. One obtains differential-topological invariants of a 4-manifold by applying the above scheme to the moduli spaces of instantons [the author, Topology 29, 257&ndash;315 (1990; <a href="/0715.57007">Zbl&nbsp;0715.57007</a>)] (although one also has to take account of various technical difficulties, for example the compactness of the moduli spaces). One can seek general procedures for calculating these invariants, in the hope that these calculations will yield new information about the structure of 4-manifolds. In particular one would like to set up &ldquo;gluing techniques&rdquo; for analyzing the invariants when the base manifold is subjected to various surgical operations. To a certain extent the theory of Floer homology provides a scheme for such an analysis. Let \(X\) be an oriented 4-manifold (possibly disconnected) with two boundary components \(Y\), \(\overline Y\) which are identified by an orientation-reversing diffeomorphism, and let \(\widetilde X\) be the closed manifold obtained by pasting \(Y\) to \(\overline Y\). If \(Y\) is a homology sphere then <span class="zbmathjax-textit">A. Floer</span>&rsquo;s theory [Commun. Math. Phys. 118, 215&ndash;240 (1988; <a href="/0684.53027">Zbl&nbsp;0684.53027</a>)] provides groups \(HF(Y)\), \(HF(\overline Y)\) and a pairing \(HF(Y) \otimes HF(\overline Y) \to {\mathbb{Z}}\). One defines invariants of the manifold-with-boundary \(X\) which take values in the tensor product \(HF(Y) \otimes HF (\overline Y)\) and the invariants of the closed manifold \(\widetilde X\) are obtained from these by the above pairing. However the theory does not, at present, encompass all the surgery operations that one would like to perform (although a number of authors have studied extensions of Floer&rsquo;s theory and related gluing questions [<span class="zbmathjax-textit">D. M. Austin</span> and <span class="zbmathjax-textit">P. J. Braam</span>, Equivariant Floer cohomology for rational homology 3-spheres, Preprint; <span class="zbmathjax-textit">K. Fukaya</span>, Instanton homology for oriented 3-manifolds, Preprint; <span class="zbmathjax-textit">C. H. Taubes</span>, \(L^2\)-moduli spaces on 4-manifolds with cylindrical ends. Cambridge, MA: International Press (1993; <a href="/0830.58004">Zbl&nbsp;0830.58004</a>); <span class="zbmathjax-textit">J. W. Morgan</span>, <span class="zbmathjax-textit">T. Mrowka</span> and <span class="zbmathjax-textit">D. Ruberman</span>, The \(L^2\)-moduli space and a vanishing theorem for Donaldson polynomial invariants. Cambridge, MA: International Press (1994; <a href="/0830.58005">Zbl&nbsp;0830.58005</a>)]). The strategy behind the present paper is to study the lower dimensional case of surfaces in the hope this will yield a good model for the more complicated questions in four dimensions.<br class="zbmathjax-paragraph">For the entire collection see [<a href="/0780.00031">Zbl&nbsp;0780.00031</a>].</div>
            <div class="clear"></div>
            
                <br>
                <div class="citations"><div class="clear"><a href="/?q=ci%3A554846">Cited in <strong>5</strong> Reviews</a></div><div class="clear"><a href="/?q=rf%3A554846">Cited in <strong>13</strong> Documents</a></div></div>
            
